ellska||\n|}\n\n{{Commons category|The Amazing Meeting}}\n<gallery>\nFile:TAM1 Collage.jpg|Jeff Wagg shows TAM2 memorabilia from Tuscany Casino - 2004\nFile:TAM2 Collage.JPG|Jeff Wagg shows TAM3 memorabilia from Stardust Casino - 2005\nFile:James Randi levates Ed Lu at TAM 4.jpg|Randi levates astronaut [[Ed Lu]] at TAM 4 - 2006\nFile:Murray Gell-Mann at TAM4.jpg|[[Murray Gell-Mann]] at TAM4 - 2006\nFile:Christopher Hitchens.jpg|[[Christopher Hitchens]] TAM 5, 2007\nFile:TreyParker MattStone 2007.jpg|[[Trey Parker]] and [[Matt Stone]] TAM 5, 2007\nFile:TAM 6 - Dr. Neil DeGrasse Tyson.jpg|[[Neil DeGrasse Tyson]] TAM 6, 2008\nFile:Timminchin tamlondon 2009.jpg|[[Tim Minchin]] TAM London 2009\nFile:Ken-RayPaulRandiKen photo at TAM8.jpg|[[Ray Hyman]], [[Paul Kurtz]], [[James Randi]], and [[Kendrick Frazier|Ken Frazier]] at TAM8, July 2010\nFile:JREF TAM9 Beard Photo.jpg|The [[IIG]] tribute to James Randi - TAM 9 - July 16, 2011\nFile:HorsesAssTAM2012.jpg|[[Sylvia Browne]] protest led by mentalist [[Mark Edward]] TAM 2012\nFile:Randi Opening TAM.jpg|James Randi opens TAM 2013\nFile:Randi Table TAM13.jpg|James Randi at TAM13 - 2015\n</gallery>\n\n==References==\n\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.amazingmeeting.com/ Official website]\n* [http://lanyrd.com/series/tam/ [[Lanyrd]] site with all TAM events listed]\n\n{{Skeptical conferences}}\n{{James Randi}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Amaz!ng Meeting}}\n[[Category:Skeptic organizations in the United States]]\n[[Category:Skeptic conferences]]\n[[Category:Recurring events established in 2003]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox convention\n| name       = The Amazing Meeting\n| image      = TamLogo.png\n| caption    =\n| status     = Inactive<ref name=\"frustrated\">{{Cite web |url=https://skeptoid.com/blog/2016/03/19/are-you-frustrated-that-tam-the-jref-are-no-more-and-the-skeptical-community-has-disintegrated/ |title=Are you frustrated that TAM & the JREF are no more, and the skeptical community has disintegrated? |author=[[Brian Dunning (author)|Brian Dunning]] |work=Skeptoid blog |date=March 19, 2016 |accessdate=October 25, 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"HallDyer\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.csicop.org/specialarticles/show/from_tam_to_csicon_an_interview_with_ray_hall_and_katie_dyer |title=From TAM to CSICon: An Interview with Ray Hall and Katie Dyer |author=[[Susan Gerbic]] |work=CSI website |publisher=CSI |date=September 22, 2016 |accessdate=October 25, 2016 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161025120620/http://www.csicop.org/specialarticles/show/from_tam_to_csicon_an_interview_with_ray_hall_and_katie_dyer |archivedate=October 25, 2016 }}</ref>\n| genre      = [[science]] and [[scientific skepticism|skepticism]]\n| venue      =\n| location   = Las Vegas, Nevada\n| country    = United States\n| first      = 2003\n| last       = 2015<ref name=\"frustrated\"/><ref name=\"HallDyer\"/>\n| organizer  = [[James Randi Educational Foundation]]\n| filing     =\n| attendance = 1,650 in 2011\n| website    = [http://www.amazingmeeting.com/ AmazingMeeting.com]\n}}\n'''The Amazing Meeting''' ('''TAM'''), stylized as '''The Amaz!ng Meeting''', was<ref name=\"frustrated\"/><ref name=\"HallDyer\"/> an annual conference that focused on [[science]], [[scientific skepticism|skepticism]], and [[critical thinking]]. The conference started in 2003<ref name=\"StollznowTAM8\">{{citation |url=http://www.csicop.org/specialarticles/show/the_amazing_meeting |author=Stollznow, Karen |authorlink=Karen Stollznow |title=The Good Word: The Amaz!ng Meeting |publisher=[[Committee for Skeptical Inquiry]] |date=July 23, 2010 |accessdate=March 1, 2012 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120119150255/http://www.csicop.org/specialarticles/show/the_amazing_meeting |archivedate=January 19, 2012 }}</ref> and was sponsored by the [[James Randi Educational Foundation]] (JREF). Perennial speakers included [[Penn & Teller]],<ref name=\"sfweekly\">{{citation|title=The Demystifying Adventures of the Amazing Randi|url=http://www.sfweekly.com/2009-08-26/news/the-demystifying-adventures-of-the-amazing-randi/|author=Mooney, Michael J.|newspaper=[[SFWeekly]]|location=San Francisco, California|date=August 26, 2009|accessdate=February 7, 2012|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110610164301/http://www.sfweekly.com/2009-08-26/news/the-demystifying-adventures-of-the-amazing-randi/|archivedate=June 10, 2011}}</ref> [[Phil Plait]], [[Michael Shermer]] and [[James Randi|James \"The Amazing\" Randi]]. Speakers at the four-day conference were selected from a variety of disciplines including scientific educators, magicians, and community activists.<ref name=DailyBeast/> Outside the plenary sessions the conference included workshops, additional panel discussions, music and magic performances and live taping of podcasts including ''[[The Skeptics' Guide to the Universe]]''.<ref name=SOTN>{{cite web|title=An Introduction To The Amaz!ng Meeting|url=http://skepticsonthe.net/an-introduction-to-the-amazng-meeting/|work=Skeptics On The .Net The online directory for everything Skeptical|publisher=Skeptics On The .Net|accessdate=March 3, 2012|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140817032808/http://skepticsonthe.net/an-introduction-to-the-amazng-meeting/|archivedate=August 17, 2014}}</ref> The final Amazing Meeting was held in July 2015.<ref name = JREFStatus/>\n\n==History and organization==\nTAM was first held in 2003, attracting around 150 attendees.<ref name=\"RomanowskiVolunteer\">{{cite web |last1=Gerbic |first1=Susan |authorlink=Susan Gerbic |title=King Of Volunteers \u2013 A Interview With Scott Romanowski |url=https://skepticalinquirer.org/exclusive/king_of_volunteers_-_a_interview_with_scott_romanowski/?/specialarticles/show/king_of_volunteers_-_a_interview_with_scott_romanowski |website=Skeptical Inquirer |accessdate=13 November 2019 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20191113021049/https://skepticalinquirer.org/exclusive/king_of_volunteers_-_a_interview_with_scott_romanowski/?/specialarticles/show/king_of_volunteers_-_a_interview_with_scott_romanowski |archivedate=13 November 2019 |date=21 August 2018}}</ref> When the [[Committee for Skeptical Inquiry|CSICOP]] conferences entered a seven-year hiatus in 2005, TAM quickly filled the gap and, with more than 1,000 attendees, grew out to become the largest U.S. skeptical conference.<ref name=\"RomanowskiVolunteer\"/><ref name=\"4decades\">{{Cite journal |last=Frazier |first=Kendrick |authorlink=Kendrick Frazier |date=March 2015 |title=Organized Skepticism: Four Decades ... and Today |url=http://www.csicop.org/si/show/organized_skepticism_four_decades_..._and_today |journal=Skeptical Inquirer |publisher=CSI |volume=39 |issue=2 |accessdate=October 25, 2016 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161003140636/http://www.csicop.org/si/show/organized_skepticism_four_decades_..._and_today |archivedate=October 3, 2016 }}</ref>\n\n[[The Skeptics Society]] and the [[Committee for Skeptical Inquiry]] were co-sponsors of the event, providing both financial and promotional support.<ref>{{cite web|title=The Amaz!ng Meeting|url=http://www.csicop.org/specialarticles/show/the_amazing_meeting|publisher=CSI|accessdate=5 February 2012|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120119150255/http://www.csicop.org/specialarticles/show/the_amazing_meeting|archivedate=19 January 2012}}</ref>\n\nPeople attended the conference for a variety of reasons. The [[Daily Beast]] reported that some saw themselves \"as waging a broad, multifront battle to drag American culture, inch by inch, away from the nonscientific and the nonlogical\".<ref name=DailyBeast/> While the organizer of TAM London, Tracy King, said \"People come to TAM because they want to learn and hear from leading speakers on subjects which interest them, but they want to have a good time doing it. Our mix of academics, comedians and writers ensures an incredible event where the public can meet like-minded people without feeling like being into science or geek stuff makes them a minority.\"<ref>{{cite web|title=TAM London: Geeks and comedians gather to celebrate critical thinking|url=https://www.theguardian.com/science/blog/2010/oct/15/tam-london-conference-critical-thinking|publisher=Guardian News and Media Limited|accessdate=March 2, 2012|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141207234730/http://www.theguardian.com/science/blog/2010/oct/15/tam-london-conference-critical-thinking|archivedate=December 7, 2014}}</ref> Magicians were also given a central role at the conference.<ref name=\"Flam\">{{cite web|last=Flam|first=Faye|authorlink=Faye Flam|title=What magicians can teach scientists about skepticism|url=http://www.newsworks.org/index.php/health-science/item/57492|publisher=NewsWorks|accessdate=August 25, 2013|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304122240/http://www.newsworks.org/index.php/health-science/item/57492|archivedate=March 4, 2016}}</ref>\n\nMagazine ''The Skeptic'' from the [[Australian Skeptics]] gave a detailed account of all lectures from the 2010 OZ event.<ref name=\"SkepticOZ\"/>\n\nRandi retired from active participation in the JREF in early 2015;<ref name=JREFStatus>{{cite web|author1=Chip Denman, [[Rick Adams (Internet pioneer)|Rick Adams]]|title=JREF Status|url=http://web.randi.org/home/jref-status|accessdate=October 25, 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170830152145/http://web.randi.org/home/jref-status|archivedate=August 30, 2017}}</ref> a final TAM was organized in his honour in July 2015. After this, the [[Committee for Skeptical Inquiry]] chose Las Vegas as the location for [[CSICon]] 2016 to fill the void.<ref name=\"frustrated\"/><ref name=\"HallDyer\"/>\n\nAt The Amaz!ng Meeting in 2011 (TAM 9) the [[Independent Investigations Group]] (IIG) organised a tribute to [[James Randi]]. The group gathered together with other attendees, put on fake white beards, and posed for a large group photo with Randi. At the [[CSICon]] in 2017, in absence of Randi, the IIG organised another group photo with leftover beards from the 2011 photo. After Randi was sent the photo, he replied, \"I\u2019m always very touched by any such expression. This is certainly no exception. You have my sincere gratitude. I suspect, however that a couple of those beards were fake. But I\u2019m in a forgiving mood at the moment. I\u2019m frankly very touched. I\u2019ll see you at the next CSICon. Thank you all.\"<ref>{{cite web |last1=Gerbic |first1=Susan |authorlink=Susan Gerbic |title=CSICon Photo Tribute to James Randi |url=https://www.csicop.org/specialarticles/show/csicon_photo_tribute_to_james_randi |website=www.csicop.org |accessdate=6 March 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Paranormal Challenge==\nBeginning in 2009, the Amazing Meeting also hosted a public test of The [[One Million Dollar Paranormal Challenge]] for the performance of any paranormal, occult or supernatural event, under proper observing conditions.<ref name=\"sfweekly\"/> At The Amazing Meeting 7, it was announced that the $1 Million Challenge prize would not expire in 2010 as previously announced.<ref>{{cite web | title=Million Dollar Challenge Update: It's not ending!|url=http://www.randi.org/site/index.php/jref-news/640-million-dollar-challenge-update-its-not-ending.html |accessdate=February 15, 2012}}</ref>\n\nClaimant Connie Sonne in 2009 failed to find target cards in sealed envelopes using a dowsing pendulum. Mentalist [[Mark Edward]] was the only person to interview her after her test; he wrote that the room was rapt in close attention, \"It was an amazing testament to just how single-minded a conference room full of skeptical non-believers could be. I dare say that even a few of the thousand assembled might have been in some way mentally rooting for Connie to win or score some significant record for her trouble. She didn\u2019t.\" She stated to Edward that it was not time for her \"powers to be revealed\" and blamed no-one for her failures, only citing that she was involved in future world-changing events.<ref>{{cite web|first=Mark|last=Edward|authorlink=Mark_Edward|title=Connie\u2019s Conundrums|url=http://www.skepticblog.org/2009/07/13/connies-conundrums/|publisher=Skeptic Blog|accessdate=September 1, 2013|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130929225121/http://www.skepticblog.org/2009/07/13/connies-conundrums/|archivedate=September 29, 2013}}</ref>\n\nIn 2013 a man from Algeria was the Million Dollar challenger, he claimed to be able to remote view objects that were held in a sealed room. He was unable to see the objects and thus failed the challenge.<ref name=\"Flam\"/>\n\nApplicant Fei Wang appeared before the skeptic audience July 2014 with the claim that he could send energy through his hand using a type of [[therapeutic touch]]. The organizers set up a double blind test involving a volunteer selected by Wang to place their hand in a box while wearing noise canceling headphones and a blindfold. Wang or the control person ([[Jamy Ian Swiss]]) depending on the roll of a die would insert their hand also in the box (not touching the volunteer) for several seconds. Swiss was selected to be the control because Wang felt that Swiss does not have the ability that is being tested. After either Wang or the Control (Swiss) had placed their hand in the box, the volunteer would state which energy was felt. Wang had to get 8 out of 9 correct in order to pass to the final Million Dollar challenge. After the volunteer was unable to feel the energy that Wang said he was sending through his hand on the first two tries, the test was concluded as it was no longer possible for Wang to win the challenge even if he was chosen correct on the remaining tries.<ref>{{cite web|title=Million Dollar Challenge|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?t=534&v=l20jQj0FZ_E|publisher=JREF|accessdate=April 28, 2015|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160313210632/https://www.youtube.com/watch?t=534&v=l20jQj0FZ_E|archivedate=March 13, 2016}}</ref>\n\nTech journalist Lee Hutchinson approached the JREF after writing an article for Ars Technica about directional [[Ethernet]] cables that claim to \"keep your audio signal completely free of electromagnetic interference\". The MDC set up a controlled double-blind demonstration with volunteers listening to two identical recordings with a randomly selected Ethernet cable, a normal one or the cable claiming to improve the listening experience. After six volunteers, the demonstration was called off, as they were unable to select the \"enhanced\" cable over the common cable.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Hutchinson|first1=Lee|title=STAFF / FROM THE MINDS OF ARS To the audiophile, this $10,000 Ethernet cable apparently makes sense In reality, one-way silver cable does nothing but make \"audiophools\" poorer.|url=https://arstechnica.com/staff/2015/02/to-the-audiophile-this-10000-ethernet-cable-apparently-makes-sense/|website=Ars Technica|accessdate=July 25, 2015|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150721012407/http://arstechnica.com/staff/2015/02/to-the-audiophile-this-10000-ethernet-cable-apparently-makes-sense/|archivedate=July 21, 2015}}</ref>\n\nThe tests included:\n\n{|width=\"100%\" border=\"1\" class=\"wikitable\"\n|-valign=\"top\"\n!'''Year'''\n!'''Challenger'''\n!'''Ability'''\n!'''Test'''\n!'''Results'''\n!'''Notes'''\n|-valign=\"top\"\n|2009\n|Connie Sonne\n|Dowsing (Pendulum)\n|Identify playing cards in sealed envelope.\n|Failed\n|\n|-valign=\"top\"\n|2010\n|Anita Ikonen\n|Medical Dowsing\n|Determine by observation which of 5 subjects was missing a kidney.\n|Failed\n|Billed as \"demonstration\" not \"test\"\n|-valign=\"top\"\n|2011\n|colspan=\"5\"|''No challenger available''\n|-\n|-\n|-\n|-valign=\"top\"\n|2012\n|Andrew Needles\n|Performance-enhancing bracelet\n|Distinguish participants wearing real product significant number of times\n|Failed\n|Claimant abandoned test in progress\n|-valign=\"top\"\n|2013\n|Brahim Addoun\n|Remote viewing\n|Remotely identify 3 of 20 objects\n|Failed\n|\n|-valign=\"top\n|2014\n|Fei Wang\n|Can send energy through his hand that can be felt by another person\n|Electricity to the hand felt correctly 8 out of 9 times\n|Failed\n|\n|-\n|-valign=\"top\n|2015\n|''No claimant'' - \"Demonstration test\"\n|[[Ethernet]] cables that are claimed to be \"directional\".\n|Volunteers were played sound twice and were asked to determine which cable had the highest sound quality\n|Failed\n|\n|}\n<gallery>\nFile:Million Dollar Challenge - Connie Sonne.jpg|Connie Sonne & [[Banachek]] at TAM 2009\nFile:Challenge 234.jpg|[[Hal Bidlack]], [[Derek Colanduno]] and others are \"viewed\" by paranormal applicant for a missing kidney.\nFile:MillionDollarChallenge2012.jpg|Performance-enhancing bracelet at TAM 2012\nFile:TAM11-3163.jpg|The 3 remote viewing objects from TAM 2013\nFile:TAM11-3125.jpg|Richard Saunders in remote viewing room at TAM 2013\nFile:MDC 2014.jpg|Fei Wang is applicant, [[Banachek]] and [[Richard Saunders (skeptic)|Richard Saunders]] are assisting TAM 2014\nFile:MDC TAM13.jpg |Demonstration test of [[Ethernet]] cables TAM13 - Grace Denman and volunteers - 2015\n</gallery>\n\n==Special awards==\nThe James Randi Education Foundation presented special awards at the Amazing Meeting to people who they label champions of skepticism. [[Robert S. Lancaster]] received the 2009 Citizen Skeptic award for his work on the website ''Stop Sylvia'' which critically examines the claims of self-proclaimed psychic [[Sylvia Browne]].<ref>{{Citation | title=Ep. #106 - TAM 7 Wrap-Up | date=July 13, 2009 | url=http://www.skepticality.com/tam-7-wrap-up/ | author=Swoopy | authorlink=Robynn McCarthy | first2=Derek | last2=Colanduno | author2-link=Derek Colanduno | work=[[Skepticality]] | publisher=[[Skeptic (U.S. magazine)|Skeptic Magazine]] | accessdate=November 27, 2011 | url-status=live | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110708065934/http://www.skepticality.com/tam-7-wrap-up/ | archivedate=July 8, 2011 }}</ref>\n\nAt that year's TAM London the award for Outstanding Contribution to Skepticism went to [[Simon Singh]] in recognition for his successful appeal against a libel charge by the British Chiropractic Association.<ref>{{cite web|title=TAM London 2009: James Randi Award goes to Simon Singh|url=https://www.flickr.com/photos/prokrastinuft/4254090906/|accessdate=March 2, 2012|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141211125945/https://www.flickr.com/photos/prokrastinuft/4254090906/|archivedate=December 11, 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn 2010 at TAM London then 15-year-old [[Rhys Morgan]] received a special grassroots skepticism award from Randi.<ref name=Londonist>{{cite web|title=Review: The Amazing Meeting London|url=http://londonist.com/2010/10/review_the_amazing_meeting_london.php|publisher=Londonist|accessdate=March 2, 2012|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141205140748/http://londonist.com/2010/10/review_the_amazing_meeting_london.php|archivedate=December 5, 2014}}</ref>\n\nReed Esau received the James Randi Award for Skepticism in the Public Interest at TAM 2012 for his work inventing [[SkeptiCamp]].\n\nAt TAM 2013, the award winner was [[Susan Gerbic]] for her work with crowd-sourced activism, specifically her work as the leader of the Guerrilla Skepticism on Wikipedia (GSoW) project.\n\nThe award reads:\n\n{{Quote|''With gratitude for your steadfast advocacy for skepticism on the World Wide Web and at the grass roots''}}\n\n<gallery>\nFile:Andrus and Randi.jpg|Magician [[Jerry Andrus]] and [[James Randi]] TAM4 2006\nFile:Robert Lancaster receives 2009 JREF Citizen Skeptic Award.JPG|[[Robert S. Lancaster]] with family and [[James Randi]] receiving the Citizen Skeptic Award, July 11, 2009\nFile:RhysMorgan1.png|[[Rhys Morgan]] receiving the James Randi Award for Grassroots Activism TAM London, October 16, 2010\nFile:Reed Esau with TAM award.jpg|Reed Esau, Founder of [[SkeptiCamp]], Receiving James Randi Award for Skepticism in the Public Interest, at TAM 2012\nFile:JREFGerbicTAMaward.jpg|[[D. J. Grothe|D.J. Grothe]], [[Susan Gerbic]], James Randi - Gerbic is presented with the James Randi award for Skepticism in the Public Interest \n</gallery>\n\n==Locations and dates==\nIn addition to the Las Vegas-based conferences the JREF also sponsored international TAM conferences, with the first TAM London taking place in 2009 and TAM Australia in 2010, co-sponsored by [[Australian Skeptics]],<ref name=\"skeptics1\">{{cite web |url=http://www.skeptics.com.au/latest/announcements/australian-skeptics-announce-tamaustralia2010/ |title=Australian Skeptics Announce: TAM! Australia 2010 &#124; Australian Skeptics |publisher=Skeptics.com.au |accessdate=May 13, 2010 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120505191549/http://www.skeptics.com.au/latest/announcements/australian-skeptics-announce-tamaustralia2010/ |archivedate=May 5, 2012 }}</ref> in 2010.<ref name=SOTN /> A related series of events titled ''The Amazing Adventure'' has been held featuring trips to the Bermuda Triangle (2007), an Alaskan cruise (2007), the Galapagos Islands (2008), Mexico (2009), and the Caribbean (2010).<ref>{{cite web|title=Past Meetings|url=http://www.randi.org/site/index.php/amazing-meeting.html|work=The Amazing Meeting|publisher=James Randi Educational Foundation|accessdate=March 3, 2012}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Dates !! Location !! Name !! Speakers !! Attendance and notes\n|-\n|January 31 - February 2, 2003|| Fort Lauderdale, FL || The Amaz!ing Meeting || [[James Randi]], Jose Alvarez, [[Jerry Andrus]], [[Marvin Minsky]], John Brown, [[Hal Bidlack]], [[Jack Horkheimer]], [[Phil Plait]], [[James Underdown]], Eric Krieg, Alan Koslow, Lisa Goodlin, [[Andrew Mayne]], Dan Garvin, Jack LaTona, Chip Denman, [[Jamy Ian Swiss]], Ray Hall, [[Michael Shermer]], Grace Denman,