{"title_page": "Bengalis in Pakistan", "text_new": "{{POV|date=April 2018}}\n{{more citations needed|date=September 2017}}\n{{Use Pakistani English|date=February 2017}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2012}}\n{{Infobox ethnic group\n|group=Bengalis in Pakistan\n|pop=2,000,000<ref>{{cite web|url=https://tribune.com.pk/story/322325/five-million-illegal-immigrants-residing-in-pakistan/|title=Five million illegal immigrants residing in Pakistan - The Express Tribune|date=16 January 2012|publisher=}}</ref>\n|regions= Mainly in cities across [[Sindh]]\n|langs=[[Bengali language|Bengali]]{{\u00b7}}[[Urdu]]{{\u00b7}}English <small>([[Pakistani English]])</small>\n|rels=[[Christianity]], [[Islam]] and [[Hinduism]]\n}}\n\n'''Pakistani Bengalis''' ({{lang-ur|{{Nastaliq|\u067e\u0627\u06a9\u0633\u062a\u0627\u0646\u06cc \u0628\u0646\u06af\u0627\u0644\u06cc }}}}) are [[Pakistanis|Pakistani]] citizens of [[Bengalis|Bengali]] heritage, who had lived in either [[West Pakistan]] or [[East Pakistan]] prior to 1971 or who migrated from [[Bangladesh]] after 1971; although according to social activists in Pakistan, economic migrants have mostly moved out because it is no longer profitable to work and earn in Pakistan due to the [[Pakistani rupee]] being weaker than the [[Bangladeshi taka]].<ref>{{cite web |url= https://www.dawn.com/news/1414503/bengalis-of-karachi-demand-urgent-resolution-to-identity-problem |title= Bengalis of Karachi demand urgent resolution to identity problem |author= Bilal Karim Mughal, Zehra Naqvi |date= 16 June 2018 |publisher= Dawn.com }}</ref> Most Pakistani Bengalis, are bilingual speaking both [[Urdu]] and [[Bengali language|Bengali]] and are mainly settled in [[Karachi]]. Bengalis that arrived in Pakistan before 1971 have now [[Cultural assimilation|assimilated]] with the Urdu-speaking people in Karachi. Persons migrated to Pakistan (West Pakistan formerly) from East Pakistan (present day Bangladesh) are still considered Pakistanis with the citizenship and origin. They are still considered as Pakistani origins and not really Bangladeshi origins because of not holding Bangladeshi citizenship and wish to stay and be a Pakistani and living in Pakistan. Any person is also a Pakistani origin if He/She is a foreign national residing abroad of Bangladeshi origin but wish to be a Pakistani origin and whose parents or grandparents are born in East Pakistan (after 14 august 1971) (present day Bangladesh) could acquire Pakistani citizenship (Pakistan Citizenship act 1951,Citizenship at the date of commencement of this Act) and live in Pakistan like every Citizen of Pakistan and could be considered a Pakistani origin\n\n==History==\n===Pre-1947===\nThe founding members of the Pakistani Bengali community were early migrants from [[East Bengal]] who arrived in [[Sindh]] during the early 20th century. This community of early Bengali settlers [[Cultural assimilation|assimilated]] into Pakistani culture and adopted [[Urdu language|Urdu]] or became bilingual [[Bengali language|Bengali]] speakers.\n\n===1947-1971===\nAfter Pakistan's independence in 1947, a large influx of Bengalis arrived in Karachi from [[East Pakistan]] to [[West Pakistan]]. In 1971, some Bengalis opted to return to the newly independent Bangladesh while others opted to remain in Pakistan.\n\n===Post-1971===\nThousands of illegal Bangladeshi immigrants arrived in Pakistan in the 1980s, while Bangladesh was battling extreme poverty.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://asia.nikkei.com/magazine/20160407-BRIDGING-THE-GAP/Politics-Economy/Bangladeshi-immigrants-in-Pakistan-find-it-hard-to-go-home?page=1|title=Bangladeshi immigrants in Pakistan find it hard to go home|website=Nikkei Asian Review}}</ref> By 1995, continuous migration of Bangladeshis crossed the 2,500,000 mark. During the administration of [[Prime Minister of Pakistan|Prime Minister]] [[Benazir Bhutto]], some top advisers became concerned with the large Bangladeshi migrant population, afraid they could become the second largest group in Karachi after Urdu-speaking [[Muhajir people]] and disturb sensitive demographics. Accordingly, Bhutto ordered a crackdown and deportation on Bangladeshi immigrants. Benazir Bhutto's action strained and created tensions in [[Bangladesh\u2013Pakistan relations]], with [[Khaleda Zia]], who was in power in [[Dhaka]] during the time, refusing to accept the deportees and reportedly sending two planeloads back towards Pakistan and Muslim political parties in Pakistan criticising Bhutto and dubbing the crackdown as anti-Islamic. She was ultimately forced to abandon the order.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.southasiaanalysis.org/%5Cpapers6%5Cpaper597.html |title=Indo-Bangladesh Standoff |last=Rahman |first=B. |date=4 February 2003 |website=South Asia Analysis Group |archive-url=https://archive.is/20120912000030/http://www.southasiaanalysis.org/%5Cpapers6%5Cpaper597.html |archive-date=12 September 2012 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Five million illegal immigrants residing in Pakistan |url=http://tribune.com.pk/story/322325/five-million-illegal-immigrants-residing-in-pakistan/ |date=16 January 2012 |work=Express Tribune |access-date=26 December 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Demographics==\nAccording to Shaikh Muhammad Feroze, chairman of the Pakistani Bengali Action Committee, over 200 settlements of Bengali-speaking people exist in Pakistan (mainly in [[Sindh]]) of which 132 are in Karachi while other smaller communities exist in [[Thatta]], [[Badin]], [[Hyderabad, Pakistan|Hyderabad]], [[Tando Adam]] and [[Lahore]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://tribune.com.pk/story/347968/fringe-pakistan-bengali-speaking-pakistanis-demand-right-to-vote/|title=Fringe Pakistan: Bengali-speaking Pakistanis demand right to vote|last=|first=|date=10 March 2012|work=Express Tribune|quote=Shaikh Muhammad Feroze, the chairman of the committee, said during a press conference on Friday that political parties and the government should acknowledge the sacrifices of their ancestors. 'We live in Sindh and feel proud to be called Sindhis rather than Bengalis. We appeal to Sindhi nationalists and Sindhis to help us in our struggle,' he added. He said that Bengali-speaking people were not given educational rights as they did not possess national identity cards. 'Our children can't get an education after matriculation because colleges ask for the identity cards but the National Database Registration Authority has never accepted us as Pakistani citizens.' Shaikh said that over three million Bengalis and Biharis were grateful to the government for accepting them as Pakistani citizens. 'We postponed a hunger strike planned for March 25 after the government made decisions,' he added. 'We can go on a hunger strike, if our rights are not given.' He claimed that there were 200 settlements of Bengali-speaking people across the country, including 132 in Karachi. They populate different parts of Pakistan, including Thatta, Badin, Hyderabad, Tando Adam and Lahore.|access-date=26 December 2016}}</ref> There are numerous [[Bengali people|Bengali]] colonies in Karachi, often called \"Mini Bangladesh\" (or East Pakistan Colony in memorandum),<ref name=\"Outlook\">{{cite journal |last1=Tohid |first1=Owais |last2=Mahmud |first2=Arshad |date=29 November 1995 |title=Homeless In Karachi |url=http://www.outlookindia.com/article.aspx?200305 |journal=[[Outlook (Indian magazine)|Outlook]] |accessdate = 2010-03-02}}</ref> such as [[Machar Colony]], [[Musa Colony]] and [[Chittagong Colony]]. Colorful Bengali signboards, Bhashani caps, [[lungi]]s and [[kurta]]s are often seen in these areas of Karachi and remain unique.<ref name=\"Outlook\"/> The Chittagong Colony has a [[bazaar]], which is famous throughout Pakistan as the center for [[Dhakai|Dhaka cloth]].<ref name=\"Daily Times\">{{cite news|last=Naqvi |first=Abbas |date=17 December 2006 |title=Falling back |url=http://www.dailytimes.com.pk/default.asp?page=2006\\story_17-12-2006_pg12_3 |newspaper=Daily Times |accessdate=19 January 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131009194726/http://www.dailytimes.com.pk/default.asp?page=2006%5C12%5C17%5Cstory_17-12-2006_pg12_3 |archivedate=9 October 2013 |df=dmy }}</ref> In more recent times, the Bengali population has seen a decline as the perilous journey from Bangladesh has been fraught with danger and tense borders.<ref>{{cite magazine |last=Bloch |first=Hannah |date=25 September 2000 |title=You Can't Get There From Here |url=http://edition.cnn.com/ASIANOW/time/magazine/2000/0925/pakistan.stateless.html |magazine=Time Asia}}</ref><ref name=\"refworld.org\">http://www.refworld.org/pdfid/4b6fe2dd0.pdf</ref> Furthermore, given the tense ethnic rivalries and lack of social welcome in Pakistan, Bengalis have now been traveling elsewhere.<ref name=\"refworld.org\"/>\n\n==Notable people==\n* [[Khwaja Hassan Askari]], the last [[Nawab of Dhaka]].\n* [[Khwaja Khairuddin]], a Pakistani Politician.\n* [[Khwaja Shahabuddin]], a Pakistani Politician & diplomat.\n* [[Alamgir (pop singer)|Alamgir]], a popular [[Pakistani pop]] singer in the 1970s and 80s.\n* [[Robin Ghosh]], Pakistani music composer and playback singer.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thenews.com.pk/latest/98047-Renowned-music-composer-Robin-Ghosh-passes-away|title=Renowned music composer Robin Ghosh passes away|publisher=}}</ref>\n* [[Shabnam]], one of Pakistan's most popular actresses.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pak101.com/c/celebrities/bio/134/Actresses/Shabnam|title=Shabnam biography, complete biography of Actresses Shabnam|website=www.pak101.com}}</ref> \n* [[Munni Begum]], a Pakistani ghazal singer\n* [[Nurul Amin]], a jurist who served as [[Prime Minister of Pakistan]].\n* [[Habibullah Bahar Chowdhury]], a politician, journalist and sportsman.\n* [[Roopa Farooki]]&nbsp;\u2013 British writer (half Pakistani, half Bangladeshi)\n* [[Tariq Fatemi]], a Pakistani diplomat who serves as the Special Assistant to the Prime Minister of Pakistan on Foreign Affairs, and previously served as Pakistan Ambassador to the United States and to the European Union.\n* [[Zaib-un-Nissa Hamidullah]], feminist writer.\n* [[Altaf Husain]], a [[Pakistan Movement]] activist and founding editor and the first editor-in-chief of [[Dawn (newspaper)|Dawn]].\n* [[Shaista Suhrawardy Ikramullah]], a prominent Pakistani female politician, diplomat and author.\n* [[Shahida Jamil]], is a Pakistani lawyer and politician.\n* [[Iskander Mirza]], a politician who served as the first [[President of Pakistan]].\n* [[Indu Mitha]], is a Pakistani exponent of [[Bharatnatyam]] and faculty member at the [[National College of Arts]]\n* Sir [[Khawaja Nazimuddin]], a conservative Pakistani politician and statesman who served as the 2nd Prime Minister of Pakistan\n* [[Abdur Rahim (judge)|Sir Abdur Rahim]], jurist and Islamic author who participated in the [[Pakistan Movement]].\n* [[Jalaludin Abdur Rahim]], [[Nietzschean]] philosopher and one of the founders of the influential [[Pakistan People's Party]]\n* [[Hamoodur Rahman]], a jurist who served as the [[Chief Justice of Pakistan]].\n* [[Najma Sadeque]],  journalist, author, and women's rights activist.\n* [[Ikram Sehgal]], Defence analyst.\n* [[Huseyn Shaheed Suhrawardy]], a politician who served as [[Prime Minister of Pakistan]].\n* [[Hasan Shaheed Suhrawardy]], [[polyglot]] scholar and diplomat, brother of the former.\n* [[Begum Akhtar Sulaiman]], Pakistani social worker, political activist and the daughter of Huseyn Shaheed Suhrawardy.\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of Pakistani Bengali films]]\n* [[Musa Colony]]\n* [[Daily Qaumi Bandhan]]\n* [[Machiara Colony]]\n* [[Chittagong Colony]]\n* [[Rohingya people in Pakistan]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.irinnews.org/Report.aspx?ReportId=77816 Bangladeshi migrants struggle in Karachi slum (video)]\n* [http://edition.cnn.com/ASIANOW/time/magazine/2000/0925/pakistan.stateless.html You Can't Get There From Here: Bengali immigrants in Pakistan now wish they'd never left Bangladesh]\n* [http://tribune.com.pk/story/530236/bengali-immigrants-in-karachi-polarised-over-violence-in-bangladesh/ Bengali immigrants in Karachi polarised over violence in Bangladesh]\n* [http://tribune.com.pk/story/460370/bengalis-afraid-of-losing-their-identity-and-rights/ Bengalis afraid of losing their identity and rights]\n* [https://books.google.com/books?id=KqTIhTWuAXcC&pg=PA249&dq=2+million+Bangladeshis+in+Pakistan#v=onepage&q=2%20million%20Bangladeshis%20in%20Pakistan The Bengal Borderland: Beyond State and Nation in South Asia]\n* [http://tribune.com.pk/story/918808/too-many-mouths-to-feed-in-karachis-slum-fishermens-colony/ Too many mouths to feed in Karachi's slum fishermen's colony]\n* [http://newslinemagazine.com/magazine/in-search-of-an-identity/ In Search of an Identity]\n* {{cite news|url=http://herald.dawn.com/news/1153771|title=The woes of Bengalis, Burmese and Iranians of Karachi|work=Dawn|first=Saher|last=Baloch|first2=Bilal Karim|last2=Mughal|date=4 June 2017}}\n* [https://www.thenews.com.pk/print/130853-cr&di-to-set-up-water-analysis-labs No CNICs for Pakistani Bengalis means no jobs for them]\n\n{{Immigration to Pakistan}}\n{{Bangladeshi diaspora}}\n{{Bangladesh\u2013Pakistan relations}}\n\n[[Category:Pakistani people of Bangladeshi descent| ]]\n[[Category:Pakistani people of Bengali descent| ]]\n[[Category:Ethnic groups in Pakistan]]\n[[Category:Bangladeshi diaspora|Pakistan]]\n[[Category:Immigration to Pakistan]]\n[[Category:Muhajir people]]\n[[Category:Muhajir communities]]\n[[Category:Refugees in Pakistan]]\n", "text_old": "{{POV|date=April 2018}}\n{{more citations needed|date=September 2017}}\n{{Use Pakistani English|date=February 2017}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2012}}\n{{Infobox ethnic group\n|group=Bengalis in Pakistan\n|pop=2,000,000<ref>{{cite web|url=https://tribune.com.pk/story/322325/five-million-illegal-immigrants-residing-in-pakistan/|title=Five million illegal immigrants residing in Pakistan - The Express Tribune|date=16 January 2012|publisher=}}</ref>\n|regions= Mainly in cities across [[Sindh]]\n|langs=[[Bengali language|Bengali]]{{\u00b7}}[[Urdu]]{{\u00b7}}English <small>([[Pakistani English]])</small>\n|rels=[[Christianity]], [[Islam]] and [[Hinduism]]\n}}\n\n'''Pakistani Bengalis''' ({{lang-ur|{{Nastaliq|\u067e\u0627\u06a9\u0633\u062a\u0627\u0646\u06cc \u0628\u0646\u06af\u0627\u0644\u06cc }}}}) are [[Pakistanis|Pakistani]] citizens of [[Bengalis|Bengali]] heritage, who had lived in either [[West Pakistan]] or [[East Pakistan]] prior to 1971 or who migrated from [[Bangladesh]] after 1971; although according to social activists in Pakistan, economic migrants have mostly moved out because it is no longer profitable to work and earn in Pakistan due to the [[Pakistani rupee]] being weaker than the [[Bangladeshi taka]].<ref>{{cite web |url= https://www.dawn.com/news/1414503/bengalis-of-karachi-demand-urgent-resolution-to-identity-problem |title= Bengalis of Karachi demand urgent resolution to identity problem |author= Bilal Karim Mughal, Zehra Naqvi |date= 16 June 2018 |publisher= Dawn.com }}</ref> Most Pakistani Bengalis, are bilingual speaking both [[Urdu]] and [[Bengali language|Bengali]] and are mainly settled in [[Karachi]]. Bengalis that arrived in Pakistan before 1971 have now [[Cultural assimilation|assimilated]] with the Urdu-speaking people in Karachi.\n\n==History==\n===Pre-1947===\nThe founding members of the Pakistani Bengali community were early migrants from [[East Bengal]] who arrived in [[Sindh]] during the early 20th century. This community of early Bengali settlers [[Cultural assimilation|assimilated]] into Pakistani culture and adopted [[Urdu language|Urdu]] or became bilingual [[Bengali language|Bengali]] speakers.\n\n===1947-1971===\nAfter Pakistan's independence in 1947, a large influx of Bengalis arrived in Karachi from [[East Pakistan]] to [[West Pakistan]]. In 1971, some Bengalis opted to return to the newly independent Bangladesh while others opted to remain in Pakistan.\n\n===Post-1971===\nThousands of illegal Bangladeshi immigrants arrived in Pakistan in the 1980s, while Bangladesh was battling extreme poverty.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://asia.nikkei.com/magazine/20160407-BRIDGING-THE-GAP/Politics-Economy/Bangladeshi-immigrants-in-Pakistan-find-it-hard-to-go-home?page=1|title=Bangladeshi immigrants in Pakistan find it hard to go home|website=Nikkei Asian Review}}</ref> By 1995, continuous migration of Bangladeshis crossed the 2,500,000 mark. During the administration of [[Prime Minister of Pakistan|Prime Minister]] [[Benazir Bhutto]], some top advisers became concerned with the large Bangladeshi migrant population, afraid they could become the second largest group in Karachi after Urdu-speaking [[Muhajir people]] and disturb sensitive demographics. Accordingly, Bhutto ordered a crackdown and deportation on Bangladeshi immigrants. Benazir Bhutto's action strained and created tensions in [[Bangladesh\u2013Pakistan relations]], with [[Khaleda Zia]], who was in power in [[Dhaka]] during the time, refusing to accept the deportees and reportedly sending two planeloads back towards Pakistan and Muslim political parties in Pakistan criticising Bhutto and dubbing the crackdown as anti-Islamic. She was ultimately forced to abandon the order.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.southasiaanalysis.org/%5Cpapers6%5Cpaper597.html |title=Indo-Bangladesh Standoff |last=Rahman |first=B. |date=4 February 2003 |website=South Asia Analysis Group |archive-url=https://archive.is/20120912000030/http://www.southasiaanalysis.org/%5Cpapers6%5Cpaper597.html |archive-date=12 September 2012 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Five million illegal immigrants residing in Pakistan |url=http://tribune.com.pk/story/322325/five-million-illegal-immigrants-residing-in-pakistan/ |date=16 January 2012 |work=Express Tribune |access-date=26 December 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Demographics==\nAccording to Shaikh Muhammad Feroze, chairman of the Pakistani Bengali Action Committee, over 200 settlements of Bengali-speaking people exist in Pakistan (mainly in [[Sindh]]) of which 132 are in Karachi while other smaller communities exist in [[Thatta]], [[Badin]], [[Hyderabad, Pakistan|Hyderabad]], [[Tando Adam]] and [[Lahore]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://tribune.com.pk/story/347968/fringe-pakistan-bengali-speaking-pakistanis-demand-right-to-vote/|title=Fringe Pakistan: Bengali-speaking Pakistanis demand right to vote|last=|first=|date=10 March 2012|work=Express Tribune|quote=Shaikh Muhammad Feroze, the chairman of the committee, said during a press conference on Friday that political parties and the government should acknowledge the sacrifices of their ancestors. 'We live in Sindh and feel proud to be called Sindhis rather than Bengalis. We appeal to Sindhi nationalists and Sindhis to help us in our struggle,' he added. He said that Bengali-speaking people were not given educational rights as they did not possess national identity cards. 'Our children can't get an education after matriculation because colleges ask for the identity cards but the National Database Registration Authority has never accepted us as Pakistani citizens.' Shaikh said that over three million Bengalis and Biharis were grateful to the government for accepting them as Pakistani citizens. 'We postponed a hunger strike planned for March 25 after the government made decisions,' he added. 'We can go on a hunger strike, if our rights are not given.' He claimed that there were 200 settlements of Bengali-speaking people across the country, including 132 in Karachi. They populate different parts of Pakistan, including Thatta, Badin, Hyderabad, Tando Adam and Lahore.|access-date=26 December 2016}}</ref> There are numerous [[Bengali people|Bengali]] colonies in Karachi, often called \"Mini Bangladesh\" (or East Pakistan Colony in memorandum),<ref name=\"Outlook\">{{cite journal |last1=Tohid |first1=Owais |last2=Mahmud |first2=Arshad |date=29 November 1995 |title=Homeless In Karachi |url=http://www.outlookindia.com/article.aspx?200305 |journal=[[Outlook (Indian magazine)|Outlook]] |accessdate = 2010-03-02}}</ref> such as [[Machar Colony]], [[Musa Colony]] and [[Chittagong Colony]]. Colorful Bengali signboards, Bhashani caps, [[lungi]]s and [[kurta]]s are often seen in these areas of Karachi and remain unique.<ref name=\"Outlook\"/> The Chittagong Colony has a [[bazaar]], which is famous throughout Pakistan as the center for [[Dhakai|Dhaka cloth]].<ref name=\"Daily Times\">{{cite news|last=Naqvi |first=Abbas |date=17 December 2006 |title=Falling back |url=http://www.dailytimes.com.pk/default.asp?page=2006\\story_17-12-2006_pg12_3 |newspaper=Daily Times |accessdate=19 January 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131009194726/http://www.dailytimes.com.pk/default.asp?page=2006%5C12%5C17%5Cstory_17-12-2006_pg12_3 |archivedate=9 October 2013 |df=dmy }}</ref> In more recent times, the Bengali population has seen a decline as the perilous journey from Bangladesh has been fraught with danger and tense borders.<ref>{{cite magazine |last=Bloch |first=Hannah |date=25 September 2000 |title=You Can't Get There From Here |url=http://edition.cnn.com/ASIANOW/time/magazine/2000/0925/pakistan.stateless.html |magazine=Time Asia}}</ref><ref name=\"refworld.org\">http://www.refworld.org/pdfid/4b6fe2dd0.pdf</ref> Furthermore, given the tense ethnic rivalries and lack of social welcome in Pakistan, Bengalis have now been traveling elsewhere.<ref name=\"refworld.org\"/>\n\n==Notable people==\n* [[Khwaja Hassan Askari]], the last [[Nawab of Dhaka]].\n* [[Khwaja Khairuddin]], a Pakistani Politician.\n* [[Khwaja Shahabuddin]], a Pakistani Politician & diplomat.\n* [[Alamgir (pop singer)|Alamgir]], a popular [[Pakistani pop]] singer in the 1970s and 80s.\n* [[Robin Ghosh]], Pakistani music composer and playback singer.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thenews.com.pk/latest/98047-Renowned-music-composer-Robin-Ghosh-passes-away|title=Renowned music composer Robin Ghosh passes away|publisher=}}</ref>\n* [[Shabnam]], one of Pakistan's most popular actresses.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pak101.com/c/celebrities/bio/134/Actresses/Shabnam|title=Shabnam biography, complete biography of Actresses Shabnam|website=www.pak101.com}}</ref> \n* [[Munni Begum]], a Pakistani ghazal singer\n* [[Nurul Amin]], a jurist who served as [[Prime Minister of Pakistan]].\n* [[Habibullah Bahar Chowdhury]], a politician, journalist and sportsman.\n* [[Roopa Farooki]]&nbsp;\u2013 British writer (half Pakistani, half Bangladeshi)\n* [[Tariq Fatemi]], a Pakistani diplomat who serves as the Special Assistant to the Prime Minister of Pakistan on Foreign Affairs, and previously served as Pakistan Ambassador to the United States and to the European Union.\n* [[Zaib-un-Nissa Hamidullah]], feminist writer.\n* [[Altaf Husain]], a [[Pakistan Movement]] activist and founding editor and the first editor-in-chief of [[Dawn (newspaper)|Dawn]].\n* [[Shaista Suhrawardy Ikramullah]], a prominent Pakistani female politician, diplomat and author.\n* [[Shahida Jamil]], is a Pakistani lawyer and politician.\n* [[Iskander Mirza]], a politician who served as the first [[President of Pakistan]].\n* [[Indu Mitha]], is a Pakistani exponent of [[Bharatnatyam]] and faculty member at the [[National College of Arts]]\n* Sir [[Khawaja Nazimuddin]], a conservative Pakistani politician and statesman who served as the 2nd Prime Minister of Pakistan\n* [[Abdur Rahim (judge)|Sir Abdur Rahim]], jurist and Islamic author who participated in the [[Pakistan Movement]].\n* [[Jalaludin Abdur Rahim]], [[Nietzschean]] philosopher and one of the founders of the influential [[Pakistan People's Party]]\n* [[Hamoodur Rahman]], a jurist who served as the [[Chief Justice of Pakistan]].\n* [[Najma Sadeque]],  journalist, author, and women's rights activist.\n* [[Ikram Sehgal]], Defence analyst.\n* [[Huseyn Shaheed Suhrawardy]], a politician who served as [[Prime Minister of Pakistan]].\n* [[Hasan Shaheed Suhrawardy]], [[polyglot]] scholar and diplomat, brother of the former.\n* [[Begum Akhtar Sulaiman]], Pakistani social worker, political activist and the daughter of Huseyn Shaheed Suhrawardy.\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of Pakistani Bengali films]]\n* [[Musa Colony]]\n* [[Daily Qaumi Bandhan]]\n* [[Machiara Colony]]\n* [[Chittagong Colony]]\n* [[Rohingya people in Pakistan]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.irinnews.org/Report.aspx?ReportId=77816 Bangladeshi migrants struggle in Karachi slum (video)]\n* [http://edition.cnn.com/ASIANOW/time/magazine/2000/0925/pakistan.stateless.html You Can't Get There From Here: Bengali immigrants in Pakistan now wish they'd never left Bangladesh]\n* [http://tribune.com.pk/story/530236/bengali-immigrants-in-karachi-polarised-over-violence-in-bangladesh/ Bengali immigrants in Karachi polarised over violence in Bangladesh]\n* [http://tribune.com.pk/story/460370/bengalis-afraid-of-losing-their-identity-and-rights/ Bengalis afraid of losing their identity and rights]\n* [https://books.google.com/books?id=KqTIhTWuAXcC&pg=PA249&dq=2+million+Bangladeshis+in+Pakistan#v=onepage&q=2%20million%20Bangladeshis%20in%20Pakistan The Bengal Borderland: Beyond State and Nation in South Asia]\n* [http://tribune.com.pk/story/918808/too-many-mouths-to-feed-in-karachis-slum-fishermens-colony/ Too many mouths to feed in Karachi's slum fishermen's colony]\n* [http://newslinemagazine.com/magazine/in-search-of-an-identity/ In Search of an Identity]\n* {{cite news|url=http://herald.dawn.com/news/1153771|title=The woes of Bengalis, Burmese and Iranians of Karachi|work=Dawn|first=Saher|last=Baloch|first2=Bilal Karim|last2=Mughal|date=4 June 2017}}\n* [https://www.thenews.com.pk/print/130853-cr&di-to-set-up-water-analysis-labs No CNICs for Pakistani Bengalis means no jobs for them]\n\n{{Immigration to Pakistan}}\n{{Bangladeshi diaspora}